The gymnastics wheel know as (German wheel)

The wheel was invented in 1925 by Otto Feick in Schönau an der Brend. The grandson of a blacksmith, Feick was inspired by the memory of an event from his childhood in Reichenbach, when he had tied sticks between two hoops that his grandfather had made and rolled down a hill.

In 1936, this sport was shown at the Olympic Games in Berlin, but was not presented as an Olympic discipline.

The history 
In 1896, the captivating vintage footage showcased the extraordinary Swiss acrobat family known as the Kremos performing in Paris. The short colorized and speed adjusted film was created by the Lumière brothers, highlighting the remarkable talents of the Kremo family.

Over generations, the Kremo family excelled in two circus disciplines: icarists and jugglers. Notable members included Béla Kremo and his son Kris, who achieved great fame as circus and variety stars in 19th and 20th century Europe. Kris Kremo continued the family’s legacy and became an internationally celebrated performer well into the 21st century.

The original Kremo troupe was founded around 1880 by Josef Kremo (1854-1917), whose family had Czech origins during the time of the Austro-Hungarian Empire. Josef received training from the renowned Austrian acrobatic family, the Scheffers, known for their celebrated Risley act.

Josef was married to Franzisca Allinger (1858-1940), an Austro-Hungarian equestrienne, and together they had thirteen children, with twelve eventually becoming part of the family’s Risley act. Among them, Anton, Franziska, and Viktor showcased exceptional skill by performing a challenging triple somersault on their father’s feet, a remarkable feat then and now.

The Kremo legacy continued with Sylvester (1881-1962) and Karl (1882-1958), Josef’s sons, who established their own troupes and carried on the family tradition.

Sylvester Kremo’s troupe featured him and his daughters, Sylvia and Selna. Karl Kremo’s larger ensemble included his brother Mark (1888-1945), his wife Margrit (1891-1923), and their children, Bellona, Béla, Bianca, and Bert, with occasional additional partners. Both troupes continued to enchant audiences across Europe’s leading circuses and variety theaters until the 1930s. The Karl Kremo Family gained greater renown, and Béla Kremo, one of Karl’s sons, became a world-famous juggler, preserving the illustrious legacy for generations to come.

French artist @matthieurobertortis 
 @seven_terraces_hotel. 
THE REVOLUTION OF GIRAFFES
French sculptor Matthieu Robert-Ortis utilises the transformative influence of perspective in this brilliant artwork. The sculpture depicts a pair of elegant giraffes, but when the angle of view changes, the viewer is treated to the sight of an elephant!
The running theme in his work is change of perspective.
Robert Ortis subtly inspires observers to question their perceptions and consider possibilities of a new point of view.
A video of this sculpture has garnered a staggering 85 million views on Facebook, bringing the artist and his work into the international limelight.
This is the first time that Matthieu Robert Ortis is displaying his work in Southeast Asia.
